## A Breath Before Part Four

You have now moved through the hardest terrain this book contains.

You have named the wound without flinching. You have traced what it became in you without excusing it or catastrophizing it. You have grieved what was lost without sentimentality. You have released, as best you can, the role of the judge. You have cleared away everything forgiveness was never meant to be, and you have chosen — however tentatively, however imperfectly — the thing it actually is.

What remains is not more excavation. The ground has been turned. The old things have been brought to the surface, examined, and laid down.

What comes next is different. It is not about the wound. It is about the life that exists on the other side of it — the person you are becoming as the wound loosens its grip, the cycle you are choosing to end, the freedom that is not just the absence of pain but the presence of something genuinely new.

That is the work of Part Four.

And that is the part that can be, finally, joyful.

